JavaScript Core Fundamentals – One Shot Notes
1. Variables (var, let, const) : A variable is a named memory location used to store data that can be accessed and modified during program execution.

var : var is function-scoped and allows redeclaration and reassignment.

Use case: Old JavaScript codebases.
Example 1:
var a = 10;
var a = 20;

Example 2:
function test(){
  var x = 5;
}

let : let is block-scoped and allows reassignment but not redeclaration.

Use case: Values that change.
Example 1:
let count = 1;
count = 2;

Example 2:
if(true){
  let x = 10;
}

const : const is block-scoped and cannot be reassigned.
Use case: Fixed values.
Example 1:
const PI = 3.14;

Example 2:
const siteName = "MyApp";

2. Data Types
A data type specifies what kind of value a variable can hold.
Primitive Data Types
Stored by value.
String – Text
Number – Numeric values
Boolean – true / false
Null – Intentional empty value
Undefined – Declared but not assigned
Symbol – Unique identifier
BigInt – Large numbers

Example 1:
let name = "Amjad";
let age = 25;
let active = true;

Example 2:
let value = null;
let city;

Non-Primitive Data Types
Stored by reference.
Object
Array
Function

Example 1:
let user = { name: "Amjad", age: 25 };

Example 2:
let marks = [80, 90, 70];

3. Type Conversion and Type Coercion
Type Conversion (Explicit)

Manually converting one data type to another.
Example 1:
Number("10");

Example 2:
String(50);
Type Coercion (Implicit)
JavaScript automatically converts types.

Example 1:
"5" + 2   // "52"

Example 2:
"5" - 2   // 3

4. Operators
Operators perform operations on values.
Arithmetic Operators
Used for math operations.
+, -, *, /, %, **

Example 1:
10 + 5;

Example 2:
20 * 2;

Comparison Operators
Compare values and return boolean.
==, ===, !=, !==, >, <, >=, <=

Example 1:
5 == "5";   // true

Example 2:
5 === "5";  // false

Logical Operators
Used to combine conditions.
&&, ||, !

Example 1:
age > 18 && loggedIn

Example 2:
isAdmin || isManager

Ternary Operator : Short form of if-else.
condition ? value1 : value2
Example 1:
age > 18 ? "Adult" : "Minor";

Example 2:
loggedIn ? "Home" : "Login";

Spread Operator (...)
Expands one array or object into individual elements.
One → Many

Example 1:
let arr = [1,2,3];
let newArr = [...arr,4];

Example 2:
let a = [10,20];
let b = [...a];

Rest Operator (...)
Collects multiple values into a single array.
Many → One

Example 1:
function sum(...nums){
  console.log(nums);
}

Example 2:
function order(main, ...extras){
  console.log(extras);
}

5. Control Flow
Control flow decides which code runs and in what order.
if / else
Executes code based on condition.

Example 1:

if(age >= 18){
  console.log("Adult");
}

Example 2:
if(score >= 40){
  console.log("Pass");
}else{
  console.log("Fail");
}

switch
Used when many fixed conditions exist.

Example 1:
switch(day){
  case 1: console.log("Mon"); break;
}

Example 2:
switch(role){
  case "admin": console.log("Full Access");
}

6. Loops
Loops repeat code.
for Loop
Used when number of iterations is known.

Example 1:
for(let i=0;i<5;i++){
  console.log(i);
}


Example 2:

for(let i=1;i<=3;i++){
  console.log("Hello");
}

while Loop
Runs while condition is true.
Example 1:
let i=0;
while(i<3){
  i++;
}

Example 2:
let x=5;
while(x>0){
  x--;
}

do-while Loop
Runs at least once.
Example 1:
let i=0;
do{
  i++;
}while(i<3);


Example 2:
let n=1;
do{
  n++;
}while(n<=2);

break
Stops loop completely.
Example 1:
for(let i=1;i<=5;i++){
  if(i==3) break;
}

Example 2:
while(true){
  break;
}

continue
Skips current iteration.
Example 1:
for(let i=1;i<=5;i++){
  if(i==3) continue;
  console.log(i);
}

Example 2:
for(let i=1;i<=5;i++){
  if(i%2==0) continue;
  console.log(i);
}

7. Real-Time Combined Example

Shopping Cart Total
const prices = [100,200,300];
let total = 0;

for(let p of prices){
  total += p;
}

let discount = total > 500 ? 50 : 0;
let finalAmount = total - discount;
console.log(finalAmount);
